defaultDetailed submission default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAbility to address critical health needs in remote conflict areas. In 2012, indigenous health organizations reached a target population over half a million in conflict affected areas of Burma, and trained almost 3,000 community health workers. 
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPromotion of women’s rights among ethnic communities which are traditionally extremely patriarchal. This has included extensive programming against sexual and gender based violence, including documentation and advocacy against the Burmese military’s use of rape as a weapon of war. 
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevelopment of a broad media network in the ethnic states, enabling access to information for remote marginalized communities in their own languages, and providing unique reporting on the ongoing peace process.  
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWidespread community awareness of the need for environmental protection and sustainable development, which has led to the stopping of controversial development projects, such as the 
defaultMyitsone
default dam on the Irrawaddy river in 2011, and the 
defaultTamanthi
default dam on the Chindwin river in 2013. 
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevelopment of grassroots ethnic farmers’ networks to address issues of widespread
default land grabbing. 
defaultf)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevelopment of inter-ethnic alliances in many sectors, which are promoting ethnic reconciliation, for example the Women’s League of Burma, Burma Rivers Network, Burma News International, Ethnic Community Development Forum. 
